00:00:42.556 --> 00:00:45.185
AUDIENCE: Could you talk
about coherence states?

00:00:45.185 --> 00:00:45.890
PROFESSOR: Ah.

00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:47.690
OK, well, that's
a great question.

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:51.640
So coherence states--
actually, how many people

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.420
have looked at the
optional problems?

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:55.170
Nice, OK, good.

00:00:58.550 --> 00:01:00.270
Good, so coherence
states were a topic

00:01:00.270 --> 00:01:01.750
that we touched on
the problem sets

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:07.570
and on the optional problems,
and the optional problems

00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:20.052
are mostly on the harmonic
oscillator and nice problems

00:01:20.052 --> 00:01:22.510
revealing some of the structure
of the harmonic oscillator,

00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:25.114
and it generalizes quite boldly.

00:01:25.114 --> 00:01:27.030
But here's the basic
idea of coherence states.

00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:29.040
Let me just talk you
through the basic ideas

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:31.510
rather than do any calculations.

00:01:31.510 --> 00:01:34.987
So what's the ground state
of a harmonic oscillator?

00:01:34.987 --> 00:01:36.570
What does its wave
function look like?

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:37.256
AUDIENCE: Gaussian.

00:01:37.256 --> 00:01:38.560
PROFESSOR: It's a
Gaussian, exactly.

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:40.101
It's minimum
uncertainty wave packet.

00:01:40.101 --> 00:01:41.460
How does it evolve in time?

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:42.460
AUDIENCE: Phase.

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:43.520
PROFESSOR: Yeah, phase.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:44.960
It's an energy eigenstate,
it's the ground state,

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:46.760
so it just evolves in
time with the phase.

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:49.030
So if we look at the wave
function for the ground

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:51.850
state, phi naught, it's
something like e to the minus x

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:56.472
squared over 2a squared with
some normalization coefficient,

00:01:56.472 --> 00:01:57.930
which I'm not going
to worry about.

00:02:01.830 --> 00:02:05.074
So this is a minimal
uncertainty wave packet.

00:02:05.074 --> 00:02:06.990
Its position distribution
is time independent,

00:02:06.990 --> 00:02:07.980
because it's a
stationary statement.

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:10.188
It's momentum distribution,
which is also a Gaussian,

00:02:10.188 --> 00:02:13.570
the Fourier transform,
is time independent.

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:16.420
And so this thing up to its
rotation by the overall phase

00:02:16.420 --> 00:02:19.510
just sits there and
remains a Gaussian.

00:02:19.510 --> 00:02:21.340
Now, here's a question.

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:25.610
Suppose I take my harmonic
oscillator potential,

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:31.020
and I take my Gaussian, but
I displace it a little bit.

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:34.530
It's the same ground
state, it's the same state

00:02:34.530 --> 00:02:37.730
but I've just displaced
it over a little.

00:02:37.730 --> 00:02:40.370
What do you expect to happen?

00:02:40.370 --> 00:02:43.470
How will this state
evolve in time?

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:45.980
So, we know how to
solve that problem.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:49.580
We take this state, it's a
known wave function at time 0.

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:53.040
We expand it in the basis
of energy eigenstates,

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:55.910
each energy eigenstate
evolves in time with a phase,

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:58.220
so we put in that
phase and redo the sum,

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:00.262
and recover the time
evolution of the full state.

00:03:00.262 --> 00:03:02.636
And we've done this a number
of time on the problem sets.

00:03:02.636 --> 00:03:03.162
Yeah.

00:03:03.162 --> 00:03:10.220
AUDIENCE: Would the Gaussian,
the displaced Gaussian

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:15.338
evolve the same
way, keep its width,

00:03:15.338 --> 00:03:17.310
if it had any
other initial width

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:19.581
other than the one
of the ground state?

00:03:19.581 --> 00:03:21.080
PROFESSOR: Let me
come back to that,

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:23.121
because it's a little more
of a precise question.

00:03:25.460 --> 00:03:28.340
So we know how to solve
this problem practically,

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.560
algorithmically.

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:31.666
But here's a nice fact.

00:03:31.666 --> 00:03:33.540
I'm not going to derive
any equations, that's

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:35.650
part of the point of
the optional problems,

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:37.560
but here's a nice
fact about this state.

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:39.601
So it's clearly a minimum
uncertainty wave packet

00:03:39.601 --> 00:03:41.750
because at time 0,
because it's just

00:03:41.750 --> 00:03:45.620
the same Gaussian just
translated over a little bit.

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:47.480
So what we'd expect,
naively, from solving

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:49.530
is we expand this
in Fourier modes

00:03:49.530 --> 00:03:53.420
and then we let this the
system evolve in time.

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:55.740
We let each individual
Fourier mode--

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:58.130
or, sorry, Fourier mode-- we
let each individual energy

00:03:58.130 --> 00:04:01.080
eigenstate evolve in time, pick
up a phase, and now what we get

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:02.440
is a superposition.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:05.280
Instead of sum over
n at time 0, we'd

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:08.770
have sum over n cn phi n of x.

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:13.422
Now, as a function of time,
we get e minus I omega nt,

00:04:13.422 --> 00:04:15.630
and these phases are going
to change the interference

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:17.647
from summing up all
these energy eigenstates,

00:04:17.647 --> 00:04:19.230
and so the system
will change in time.

00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:22.019
Because the way that the various
terms in the superposition

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:23.625
interfere will change in time.

00:04:23.625 --> 00:04:25.750
So very naively, what you
might expect, if you just

00:04:25.750 --> 00:04:27.190
took a random
function-- for example,

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:28.980
if I took a harmonic
oscillator potential

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:32.800
and I took some stupid function
that did something like this.

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:34.590
What would you expect
it to do over time?

00:04:34.590 --> 00:04:37.020
Well, due to all the complicated
interference effects,

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:40.190
you'd expect this to turn
into, basically, some schmutz.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:43.586
Just some crazy
interference pattern.

00:04:43.586 --> 00:04:45.460
The thing that's nice
about a coherent state,

00:04:45.460 --> 00:04:47.000
and this is where
it gets its name,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.930
is the way that all of
these interference effects

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:56.950
conspire together to evolve
the state is to leave it

00:04:56.950 --> 00:05:02.610
a Gaussian that does nothing
but translates in time.

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:05.600
A coherent state is coherent
because it remains coherently

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.800
a Gaussian as it moves along.

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:09.610
It oscillates back and forth.

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:14.200
And in fact, the peak, the
center of this Gaussian wave

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:17.040
packet, oscillates with
precisely the frequency

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:19.070
of the trap.

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:22.930
It behaves just as a classical
particle would have had you

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:25.560
displaced it from the center of
the harmonic oscillator trap,

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:26.850
it oscillates back and forth.

00:05:30.507 --> 00:05:32.590
Now, on the other hand,
you know that its momentum

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:35.276
is changing in time, right.

00:05:35.276 --> 00:05:36.650
And at any given
point, as you've

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:39.680
shown on the problem set
that's due tomorrow--

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:42.610
or you will have shown-- at
any given moment in time,

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:44.790
the momentum can be understood
as the overall phase.

00:05:44.790 --> 00:05:46.630
You could just change that
momentum by the overall phase,

00:05:46.630 --> 00:05:48.741
so it's the spatial rate
of change of the phase, e

00:05:48.741 --> 00:05:49.960
to the ikx.

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:52.890
So you know that the way the
phase depends on position

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:54.400
is changing over time.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.440
So it can't be quite so simple
that the wave function, rather

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:59.370
than the probability
distribution,

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:00.850
is remaining a
Gaussian over time.

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:03.010
It's not, it's got all
sorts of complicated phases.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:06.060
But the upshot is that the
probability distribution

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:10.180
oscillates back and forth
perfectly coherently.

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:14.010
So that seems a little
magical, and there's a nice way

00:06:14.010 --> 00:06:16.150
to understand how
that magic arises,

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:18.240
and it's to understand
the following.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:27.380
If I take a state, phi 0, but
I translate it x minus x0.

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:28.790
OK.

00:06:28.790 --> 00:06:31.514
So we know that this
state, phi 0 of x,

00:06:31.514 --> 00:06:32.930
was the ground
state, what does it

00:06:32.930 --> 00:06:35.887
mean to be the ground state
of the harmonic oscillator?

00:06:35.887 --> 00:06:37.470
How do I check if
I'm the ground state

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.700
of the harmonic oscillator?

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.221
Look, I walk up to
you, I'm like, hey,

00:06:43.221 --> 00:06:45.220
I'm the ground state of
the harmonic oscillator.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:45.880
You're suspicious.

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:46.530
What do you do?

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:47.470
AUDIENCE: Annihilate.

00:06:47.470 --> 00:06:48.050
PROFESSOR: Annihilate.

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:48.620
Exactly.

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:50.870
You act with the
annihilation operator.

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:51.810
Curse you.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:55.129
So you act with the annihilation
operator and you get 0, right.

00:06:55.129 --> 00:06:57.670
What happens if I act with the
annihilation operator on this?

00:06:57.670 --> 00:06:59.720
Is this the ground state?

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:01.381
No, it's been displaced by x0.

00:07:01.381 --> 00:07:03.880
And meanwhile, I told you that
it oscillates back and forth.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:06.296
So what happens if you act
with the annihilation operator?

00:07:06.296 --> 00:07:07.260
Should you get 0?

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:08.510
No, what are you going to get?

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:09.240
AUDIENCE: Something weird.

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:10.824
PROFESSOR: Some
random schmutz, right?

00:07:10.824 --> 00:07:12.989
If you just take a and you
act on some stupid state,

00:07:12.989 --> 00:07:14.670
you'll just get some
other stupid state.

00:07:14.670 --> 00:07:18.397
Except for Gaussians
that have been displaced,

00:07:18.397 --> 00:07:19.980
you get a constant
times the same wave

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:23.700
function, phi 0 of x minus x0.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:24.810
Aha.

00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:26.630
It turns out that these
displaced Gaussians

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:29.140
are eigenstates of the
annihilation operator.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:31.610
What does that mean?

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:34.200
Well, it means they're
coherent states.

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:36.070
And so the optional
problems are a working

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:39.870
through of the study
of the eigenfunctions

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:45.710
of the annihilation operator,
the coherent states.

00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:46.810
Is that cool?

00:07:46.810 --> 00:07:48.505
It's a state, it's
a superposition.

00:07:48.505 --> 00:07:49.880
You can think
about it like this.

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:52.036
It's a superposition of
the energy eigenstate.

00:07:52.036 --> 00:07:54.160
Any state is a superposition
of energy eigenstates,

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.076
and a coherent state is
just some particularly

00:07:56.076 --> 00:07:58.810
special superposition
of energy eigenstates.

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:00.710
So you can think about
it literally as c0 phi

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:03.620
0 plus c1 phi 1 plus c2
phi 2, blah blah blah.

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:05.160
What does the
annihilation operator

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:06.960
do, what does the
lowering operator do?

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:08.501
It takes any state
and then lowers it

00:08:08.501 --> 00:08:09.490
with some coefficient.

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:12.190
So a coherent state, an
eigenstate of the annihilation

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:14.550
operator, must be a
state such that if you

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:18.914
take c 0 phi 0 plus
c1 phi 1 plus c2 phi 2

00:08:18.914 --> 00:08:21.080
and you hit it with the
annihilation operator, which

00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:27.690
will give you see c1 phi 0 plus
c2 phi 1 divided by root 2 plus

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:31.554
dot, dot, dot-- or times
root 2 plus dot, dot, dot.

00:08:31.554 --> 00:08:32.929
It gives you the
same state back.

00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:35.570
So that gave you a relation
between the coefficients c0

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:38.110
and c1, c1 and c2, c2 and c3.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:42.280
They've all got to be suitable
multiples of each other.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:45.550
And what you can show-- and this
is something you work through,

00:08:45.550 --> 00:08:48.055
not quite in this order, on
the optional problems-- what

00:08:48.055 --> 00:08:50.190
you can show is that
doing so it gives you

00:08:50.190 --> 00:08:52.240
a translated Gaussian.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:53.710
OK.

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:55.990
So physically, that's
what a coherent state is.

00:08:55.990 --> 00:08:58.520
Another way to say what
a coherent state is,

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:00.850
it's as close to
a classical object

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:02.610
as you're going
to get by building

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:04.460
a quantum mechanical
wave function.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:07.450
It's something that behaves
just like a classical particle

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.890
in that potential
would have behaved,

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:12.460
in the harmonic
oscillator potential.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:13.710
Did that answer your question?

00:09:13.710 --> 00:09:15.420
OK.

00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:18.080
Anything else?

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:20.110
So, Matt works with
these for a living.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:22.708
Matt, do you want
to add anything?

00:09:22.708 --> 00:09:23.666
All right.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:28.440
I like these.

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:31.190
They show up all over the place.

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:34.465
This is like the spherical
cow of wave functions

00:09:34.465 --> 00:09:35.340
because it's awesome.

00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:37.550
It's an eigenfunction, it's
an annihilation operator,

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:39.285
it behaves like a
classical particle.

00:09:39.285 --> 00:09:42.790
AUDIENCE: Is there an easy
way to define coherent states

00:09:42.790 --> 00:09:45.690
in potentials where you don't
have nice operators like a?

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:46.630
PROFESSOR: No, I
mean, that's usually

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:48.070
what we mean by
a coherent state.

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:52.350
So the term coherent state
is often used interchangeably

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:54.041
to mean many different
things, which

00:09:54.041 --> 00:09:56.290
in the case of the harmonic
oscillator, are identical.

00:09:56.290 --> 00:09:59.520
One is a state
which is a Gaussian.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:00.020
OK.

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:02.680
So in the harmonic
oscillator system,

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:04.930
that's a particularly nice
state because it oscillates

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:09.984
particularly nicely and it
maintains its probability

00:10:09.984 --> 00:10:12.400
distribution as a function of
time roughly by translating,

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:13.316
possibly, some phases.

00:10:15.834 --> 00:10:17.750
But people often use the
phrase coherent state

00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:19.690
even when you're not harmonic.

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:22.480
And it's useful to keep in mind
that we're often not harmonic,

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:25.590
nothing's truly harmonic.

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.470
You had another question
a moment ago though,

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:29.550
and your question
was about the width.

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:30.050
Yeah.

00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:32.890
AUDIENCE: It just translates
without changing its width,

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:35.020
with or without changing
its shape at all.

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:36.811
If the Gaussian were
of a different width,

00:10:36.811 --> 00:10:37.810
would that still happen?

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:40.210
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it does,
although the details of how

00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:41.630
it does so are
slightly different.

00:10:41.630 --> 00:10:43.710
That's called a squeeze state.

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:45.460
The basic idea of a
squeeze state is this.

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:47.790
Suppose I have a
harmonic oscillator--

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:50.030
and this is actually
one way people

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:51.640
build squeeze
states in labs-- so

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:52.413
suppose I have a
harmonic oscillator

00:10:52.413 --> 00:10:54.130
and I put the system
in a ground state.

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:55.296
So there's its ground state.

00:10:55.296 --> 00:10:59.290
And its width is correlated with
the frequency of the potential.

00:11:01.814 --> 00:11:03.230
Now, suppose I
take this potential

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:07.230
at some moment in time and
I control the potential,

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:09.790
the potential is created by
some laser field, for example.

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:14.440
And some annoying grad student
walks over to the control panel

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.840
and doubles the
power of the laser.

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:20.227
All of a sudden, I've
squeezed the potential.

00:11:20.227 --> 00:11:22.560
But my system is already in
a state which is a Gaussian,

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:24.530
it's just the wrong Gaussian.

00:11:24.530 --> 00:11:25.620
So what does this guy do?

00:11:25.620 --> 00:11:26.453
Well, this is funny.

00:11:26.453 --> 00:11:29.964
The true ground state,
once we've squeezed,

00:11:29.964 --> 00:11:31.630
the true ground state
would be something

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:34.701
that's much narrower
in position space.

00:11:34.701 --> 00:11:36.200
I didn't draw that
very well, but it

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:38.554
would be much narrower
in position space,

00:11:38.554 --> 00:11:39.970
and thus its
distribution would be

00:11:39.970 --> 00:11:42.000
much broader in momentum space.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.240
So the state that
we put the system,

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:48.940
or we've left the system in, has
too much position uncertainty

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:51.070
and too little
momentum uncertainty.

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:53.840
It's been squeezed compared
to the normal state

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:56.200
in the delta x delta p plane.

00:11:56.200 --> 00:11:58.442
It's uncertainty relation
is still extreme,

00:11:58.442 --> 00:12:00.650
it still saturates the
uncertainty bound because it's

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:04.050
a Gaussian, but it doesn't have
the specific delta x and delta

00:12:04.050 --> 00:12:06.340
p associated with
the true ground

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:08.190
state of the squeezed potential.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:10.980
OK, so now you can ask what
does this guy do in time.

00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:12.910
And that's one of the
optional problems, too,

00:12:12.910 --> 00:12:15.410
and it has many of the nice
properties of coherent states,

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:18.541
it's periodic, it evolves much
like a classical particle,

00:12:18.541 --> 00:12:20.040
but it's uncertainties
are different

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:22.240
and they change shape.

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:24.770
It's an interesting story,
that's the squeezed state.

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:25.632
Yeah.

00:12:25.632 --> 00:12:29.040
