Is it straight,
is it wiggly, does

00:48:15.630 --> 00:48:17.800
it have some complicated shape.

00:48:17.800 --> 00:48:18.890
How do you measure that?

00:48:18.890 --> 00:48:20.420
Well, you might measure
it by just looking.

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:22.044
But imagine you can't,
for some reason.

00:48:22.044 --> 00:48:24.270
For whatever, it's in a box
or you can't look at it.

00:48:24.270 --> 00:48:26.010
Maybe it's just
preposterously small.

00:48:26.010 --> 00:48:29.356
How can you deduce what
the shape of that hill is?

00:48:29.356 --> 00:48:30.730
Well, one way to
do it is to send

00:48:30.730 --> 00:48:33.460
in particles as a function of
energy, more and more energy,

00:48:33.460 --> 00:48:36.360
and measure the probability
that they transmit.

00:48:36.360 --> 00:48:37.010
OK.

00:48:37.010 --> 00:48:40.370
Now if you do so and you get
this graph as a function of e,

00:48:40.370 --> 00:48:42.700
what do you deduce?

00:48:42.700 --> 00:48:45.480
You deduce that the barrier
that you're scattering off of

00:48:45.480 --> 00:48:48.960
is a square step
with this height v0.

00:48:52.070 --> 00:48:53.150
Are we cool with that?

00:48:53.150 --> 00:48:55.290
So apparently, just
look at the transmission

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:58.070
amplitudes, the
transition probabilities,

00:48:58.070 --> 00:49:00.270
you can deduce at
least something

00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:02.254
of the form of the potential.

00:49:02.254 --> 00:49:03.170
Which is kind of cool.

00:49:03.170 --> 00:49:04.545
If you didn't know
the potential,

00:49:04.545 --> 00:49:07.000
you could figure
out what it was.

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.696
And this turns out to be a
very general statement that you

00:49:09.696 --> 00:49:11.696
can deduce an enormous
amount, and as we'll see,

00:49:11.696 --> 00:49:13.310
you can, in fact,
deduce basically

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:15.230
everything you want
of the potential

00:49:15.230 --> 00:49:18.840
from knowing about the
transmission probabilities

00:49:18.840 --> 00:49:22.240
as well as the phase shift,
the transmission amplitudes.

00:49:22.240 --> 00:49:24.334
So this is the basic
goal of scattering.

00:49:24.334 --> 00:49:25.750
And so the way I
want you to think

00:49:25.750 --> 00:49:28.390
about it is imagine, for
example, that someone

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:29.660
hands you an object.

00:49:29.660 --> 00:49:30.890
A box.

00:49:30.890 --> 00:49:34.610
And the box has an in port
and it has an out port.

00:49:34.610 --> 00:49:36.380
And they allow you
to send in particles

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:38.535
as a function of energy
and measure transmission

00:49:38.535 --> 00:49:41.035
and reflection, you can measure
transmission and reflection.

00:49:41.035 --> 00:49:44.350
Just like I'm measuring
transmission off of your faces

00:49:44.350 --> 00:49:47.760
right now, from the
light from above.

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:51.725
So suppose that you do so, put
it on your test stand and you

00:49:51.725 --> 00:49:52.600
measure transmission.

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:54.750
You measure transmission
as a function of energy,

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:56.800
and you observe the following.

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:58.500
The transmission as
a function of energy

00:49:58.500 --> 00:50:03.770
is small up until some point,
and then at some point,

00:50:03.770 --> 00:50:07.260
which may be the minimum energy
you can meaningfully probe,

00:50:07.260 --> 00:50:08.620
you get something like this.

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:21.987
So here's the transmission
as a function of energy.

00:50:21.987 --> 00:50:22.820
So what can you say?

00:50:25.534 --> 00:50:26.950
If this is all the
information you

00:50:26.950 --> 00:50:28.470
have about what's going
on inside the box,

00:50:28.470 --> 00:50:30.620
what can you deduce about
the thing inside the box?

00:50:33.340 --> 00:50:34.900
One thing you can
deduce is that it

00:50:34.900 --> 00:50:42.130
looks kind of like a potential
with height around v0.

00:50:42.130 --> 00:50:44.500
It looks kind of like a
potential step with some height

00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:45.380
v0.

00:50:45.380 --> 00:50:48.460
This is asymptoting to 1.

00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:53.070
However, it's not, because it
has these oscillations in it.

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:55.720
So there's more to the potential
than just a barrier of height

00:50:55.720 --> 00:50:56.885
v0.

00:50:56.885 --> 00:50:59.260
What I want to show you is
that you can deduce everything

00:50:59.260 --> 00:51:02.790
about that potential, and
that's the point of scattering.

00:51:02.790 --> 00:51:05.010
So let's do it.

00:51:05.010 --> 00:51:11.600
So the goal here, again, to say
it differently, is what's v0?

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:13.866
What is v of x?

00:51:13.866 --> 00:51:15.740
Not just the height,
but the total potential.

00:51:18.152 --> 00:51:19.860
So another way to say
this, let me set up

00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:22.457
a precise version
of this question.

00:51:22.457 --> 00:51:24.040
I want to be able
to do the following.

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:26.623
I want to take a system that has
a potential which is constant

00:51:26.623 --> 00:51:31.670
up to some point
which I'll call 0,

00:51:31.670 --> 00:51:34.660
and then again from some
point, which I'll call L,

00:51:34.660 --> 00:51:35.860
is constant again.

00:51:35.860 --> 00:51:39.940
And inside, I don't know
what the potential is.

00:51:43.569 --> 00:51:45.360
So in here, there's
some unknown potential,

00:51:45.360 --> 00:51:47.480
v of x, which is
some crazy thing.

00:51:47.480 --> 00:51:48.660
It could be doing anything.

00:51:48.660 --> 00:51:54.230
It could be some crazy-- it
could have horns and whatever.

00:51:54.230 --> 00:51:57.287
It could be awful.

00:51:57.287 --> 00:51:59.620
But the potential is constant
if you go far enough away,

00:51:59.620 --> 00:52:01.953
and the potential is constant
if you go far enough away.

00:52:01.953 --> 00:52:05.980
A good example of this
is a hydrogen atom.

00:52:05.980 --> 00:52:08.380
It's neutral but there's
a clearly and complicated

00:52:08.380 --> 00:52:10.550
potential inside because
the proton and the electron

00:52:10.550 --> 00:52:13.350
are moving around in there in
some quantum state, anyway,

00:52:13.350 --> 00:52:15.366
and if you send something
at it, far away, it's

00:52:15.366 --> 00:52:16.240
as if it's not there.

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:18.950
But close by, you know there
are strong electrostatic forces.

00:52:18.950 --> 00:52:21.325
And so the question is what
you learn about those forces,

00:52:21.325 --> 00:52:23.260
what can you learn
about the potential

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:26.120
by throwing things in from
far away, from either side.

00:52:26.120 --> 00:52:28.660
Now one thing we know already
is that out here, the wave

00:52:28.660 --> 00:52:31.170
function always-- because it's
a constant potential-- always

00:52:31.170 --> 00:52:36.750
takes the form e to the ikx
plus b e to the minus ikx.

00:52:36.750 --> 00:52:41.740
And out here it takes the
form c e to the ikx plus d

00:52:41.740 --> 00:52:44.550
e to the minus ikx.

00:52:44.550 --> 00:52:47.350
And again, this
corresponds to moving in.

00:52:47.350 --> 00:52:51.010
d is in from the right.

00:52:51.010 --> 00:52:54.330
c is out to the right.

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:56.580
b is out to the left.

00:52:56.580 --> 00:53:00.735
And a is in from the left.

00:53:00.735 --> 00:53:02.360
So again, there are
basically four kind

00:53:02.360 --> 00:53:03.430
of scattering
experiments we can do.

00:53:03.430 --> 00:53:05.250
We can send things in
from the right, which

00:53:05.250 --> 00:53:06.680
corresponds to setting a to 0.

00:53:06.680 --> 00:53:08.430
We can send things in
from the left, which

00:53:08.430 --> 00:53:10.460
corresponds to
setting t equal to 0.

00:53:10.460 --> 00:53:13.405
And all the information
about what happens in v

00:53:13.405 --> 00:53:15.740
is going to be encoded
in what's coming out,

00:53:15.740 --> 00:53:17.787
the b and c coefficients.

00:53:17.787 --> 00:53:19.370
And the way to make
that sharp is just

00:53:19.370 --> 00:53:22.817
to notice that the transmission
probability, if we compute

00:53:22.817 --> 00:53:25.150
for this system, assuming
it's forming the wave function

00:53:25.150 --> 00:53:28.450
asymptotically away from the
potential, the transmission

00:53:28.450 --> 00:53:31.800
amplitude is just
c over a squared

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:33.500
when you're sending
in from the left.

00:53:33.500 --> 00:53:41.260
And the reflection is equal
to b over a norm squared.

00:53:41.260 --> 00:53:42.987
This squared is a squared.

00:53:42.987 --> 00:53:45.070
[INAUDIBLE] function over
amplitude squared, good.

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:52.280
To learn about the transmission
and reflection coefficients,

00:53:52.280 --> 00:54:01.840
it's enough-- suffices--
to compute, to know b and c

00:54:01.840 --> 00:54:05.905
as a function of a and d.

00:54:05.905 --> 00:54:07.280
All of the scattering
information

00:54:07.280 --> 00:54:09.230
is in those coefficients
b and c for a and d.

00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:12.380
And here I'm assuming that I'm
sending in a monochromatic wave

00:54:12.380 --> 00:54:15.040
with a single, well
defined energy.

00:54:15.040 --> 00:54:18.446
I'm sending in a beam of
particles with energy e.

00:54:18.446 --> 00:54:20.070
I don't know where
they are, but I sure

00:54:20.070 --> 00:54:22.360
know what their momentum is.

00:54:22.360 --> 00:54:28.350
So some well defined beam
of particles with energy e.

00:54:28.350 --> 00:54:30.490
And these
probabilities are going

00:54:30.490 --> 00:54:33.910
to contain all the data I want.

00:54:33.910 --> 00:54:36.560
So this is the basic
project of scattering.

00:54:36.560 --> 00:54:37.250
Questions?

00:54:37.250 --> 00:54:40.040
AUDIENCE: So basically,
it only depends

00:54:40.040 --> 00:54:43.414
on the transmission-- it
only depends on the edges?

00:54:43.414 --> 00:54:44.830
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

00:54:44.830 --> 00:54:46.913
The question is, does the
transmission depend only

00:54:46.913 --> 00:54:48.430
on what you do with the edges.

00:54:48.430 --> 00:54:49.930
And here's the important thing.

00:54:49.930 --> 00:54:51.640
The transmission
depends crucially

00:54:51.640 --> 00:54:52.785
on what happens in here.

00:54:52.785 --> 00:54:54.910
For example, if this is an
infinitely high barrier,

00:54:54.910 --> 00:54:56.940
nothing's going across.

00:54:56.940 --> 00:54:59.360
So this transmission
depends on what's in here.

00:54:59.360 --> 00:55:04.870
But the point is we can deduce
just by looking far away,

00:55:04.870 --> 00:55:06.890
we can deduce the
transmission probability

00:55:06.890 --> 00:55:09.740
and amplitude just by
measuring b and c far away,

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:11.390
b and c far away.

00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:12.180
OK.

00:55:12.180 --> 00:55:13.530
So the transmission
amplitude is something

00:55:13.530 --> 00:55:14.920
you measure when very far away.

00:55:14.920 --> 00:55:17.045
You measure-- if I throw
something in from very far

00:55:17.045 --> 00:55:19.740
out here to the left, how likely
is it to get out here very

00:55:19.740 --> 00:55:21.120
far to the right?

00:55:21.120 --> 00:55:23.194
And in order to answer
that, if someone

00:55:23.194 --> 00:55:24.610
hands you the
answer to that, they

00:55:24.610 --> 00:55:26.930
must have solved
for what's inside.

00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:27.810
That the point.

00:55:27.810 --> 00:55:29.810
So knowing the answer
to that question

00:55:29.810 --> 00:55:34.282
encodes information about
what happened in between.

00:55:34.282 --> 00:55:37.560
AUDIENCE: So I guess
initially, your potential's

00:55:37.560 --> 00:55:40.511
going to-- so say it's
stuff you did earlier.

00:55:40.511 --> 00:55:42.946
The potential drops down to
the [INAUDIBLE] in the box.

00:55:42.946 --> 00:55:43.920
Is that going to be problematic?

00:55:43.920 --> 00:55:45.520
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
for simplicity, I'm

00:55:45.520 --> 00:55:47.370
going to assume that the
potential always goes to 0 when

00:55:47.370 --> 00:55:49.953
we're far away, because that's
going to be useful for modeling

00:55:49.953 --> 00:55:55.070
things like hydrogen
and, exactly.

00:55:55.070 --> 00:55:57.050
Carbon, we're going
to do diamond later

00:55:57.050 --> 00:55:59.540
in the semester,
that'll be useful.

00:55:59.540 --> 00:56:01.020
But we could repeat
this analysis

00:56:01.020 --> 00:56:04.020
by adding an extra change
in the asymptotic potential,

00:56:04.020 --> 00:56:05.870
it doesn't really change
anything important.

00:56:05.870 --> 00:56:06.828
Yeah.

00:56:06.828 --> 00:56:09.702
AUDIENCE: It looks like even
for just the simple step up

00:56:09.702 --> 00:56:12.256
[INAUDIBLE] you can't tell
from just the probabilities why

00:56:12.256 --> 00:56:14.360
the step is going
up or going down.

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:15.760
PROFESSOR: Ah, excellent.

00:56:15.760 --> 00:56:16.680
Excellent, excellent.

00:56:16.680 --> 00:56:19.430
So good, thank you for that
question, that's really great.

00:56:19.430 --> 00:56:22.700
So already, it seems
like we can't uniquely

00:56:22.700 --> 00:56:27.749
identify the potential from
the transmission probability

00:56:27.749 --> 00:56:30.040
if the transmission probability
is the same for step up

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:32.120
or step down.

00:56:32.120 --> 00:56:34.376
So what's missing?

00:56:34.376 --> 00:56:37.777
AUDIENCE: Maybe the
energy [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:37.777 --> 00:56:40.110
PROFESSOR: But we're working
with an energy [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:40.110 --> 00:56:42.670
So the energy is just
a global constant.

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:44.330
We'll see what's
missing, and what's

00:56:44.330 --> 00:56:47.130
missing is something
called the phase shift.

00:56:47.130 --> 00:56:50.390
So very good question, yes.

00:56:50.390 --> 00:56:56.078
AUDIENCE: It looks like when we
did the example for the step,

00:56:56.078 --> 00:56:58.863
that t equals [INAUDIBLE]
over a squared.

00:56:58.863 --> 00:57:01.950
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it is,
because it's the ratio.

00:57:01.950 --> 00:57:03.680
That's why I wrote
t is c over here.

00:57:03.680 --> 00:57:06.150
So t is the ratio of j over ji.

00:57:06.150 --> 00:57:14.220
And in fact, jt here is
equal to c squared times--

00:57:14.220 --> 00:57:15.834
so this is the
probability density,

00:57:15.834 --> 00:57:18.250
so it's the probability density
times the velocity, what's

00:57:18.250 --> 00:57:19.480
the effect of velocity here?

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:26.560
H bar k 2 over m, whereas
j incident is equal

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:29.450
to a squared--
probability density

00:57:29.450 --> 00:57:31.480
times the momentum there,
the velocity there--

00:57:31.480 --> 00:57:34.720
which is h bar k1 upon m.

00:57:34.720 --> 00:57:38.600
So here the ratio of j
transmitted to j incident

00:57:38.600 --> 00:57:43.265
is norm c squared k2
over norm a squared k1.

00:57:43.265 --> 00:57:44.806
AUDIENCE: So because
it's not level--

00:57:44.806 --> 00:57:46.340
PROFESSOR: Exactly, it's
because it's not level.

00:57:46.340 --> 00:57:47.800
So here, they
happen to be level,

00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:50.390
so they're only
[INAUDIBLE] factor, cancel,

00:57:50.390 --> 00:57:52.900
and the only thing that
survives is the amplitude.

00:57:52.900 --> 00:57:53.947
Good question.

00:57:53.947 --> 00:57:55.438
Yeah.

00:57:55.438 --> 00:57:59.414
AUDIENCE: For the
lead box example,

00:57:59.414 --> 00:58:02.010
is it sufficient
just to know what's

00:58:02.010 --> 00:58:05.047
reflected back to
solve the situation?

00:58:05.047 --> 00:58:06.880
PROFESSOR: So for
precisely for this reason,

00:58:06.880 --> 00:58:08.961
it's not sufficient to know t.

00:58:08.961 --> 00:58:10.460
It's not sufficient
to know t and r.

00:58:10.460 --> 00:58:12.431
But, of course, once
you know r, you know t,

00:58:12.431 --> 00:58:13.430
so you're exactly right.

00:58:13.430 --> 00:58:14.665
Once you know the
reflection probability,

00:58:14.665 --> 00:58:16.336
you know the
transmission probability,

00:58:16.336 --> 00:58:17.960
but there's one more
bit of information

00:58:17.960 --> 00:58:19.584
which we're going to
also need in order

00:58:19.584 --> 00:58:23.565
to specify the potential, which
is going to be the phase shift.

00:58:23.565 --> 00:58:25.940
But you're right, you don't
need to independently compute

00:58:25.940 --> 00:58:27.290
r and t, you can
just compute one.

00:58:27.290 --> 00:58:29.456
AUDIENCE: You need sensors
on both sides of the box,

00:58:29.456 --> 00:58:30.421
to answer my question.

00:58:30.421 --> 00:58:32.722
PROFESSOR: You
don't need sensors

00:58:32.722 --> 00:58:35.180
on both sides of the box, but
you need to do more than just

00:58:35.180 --> 00:58:37.020
do the counting problem.

00:58:37.020 --> 00:58:39.710
We'll see that.

00:58:39.710 --> 00:58:41.040
OK.

00:58:41.040 --> 00:58:44.390
So let's work out a simple
example, the simplest

00:58:44.390 --> 00:58:46.520
example of a barrier
of this kind.

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:51.810
We want constant potential,
and then ending at 0,

00:58:51.810 --> 00:58:57.160
and we want a constant again
from L going off to infinity.

00:58:57.160 --> 00:58:59.930
So what's the easiest
possible thing we could do?

00:58:59.930 --> 00:59:01.200
Step, step.

00:59:01.200 --> 00:59:04.050
We're just doing what
we've done before twice.

00:59:04.050 --> 00:59:06.520
So this is an example of
this kind of potential.

00:59:06.520 --> 00:59:10.390
It's sort of ridiculously
simple, but let's work it out.

00:59:10.390 --> 00:59:12.035
So we want scattering,
let's start out,

00:59:12.035 --> 00:59:13.090
we could do either
scattering from the left

00:59:13.090 --> 00:59:14.220
or scattering from the right.

00:59:14.220 --> 00:59:16.600
Let's start out scattering
from the left, so d equals 0,

00:59:16.600 --> 00:59:19.550
and let's study this problem.

00:59:19.550 --> 00:59:25.291
So what we know--
and let's also note

00:59:25.291 --> 00:59:26.540
that we have a choice to make.

00:59:26.540 --> 00:59:28.555
We could either study
energy below the height

00:59:28.555 --> 00:59:30.180
of the potential or
we can study energy

00:59:30.180 --> 00:59:32.749
above the height
of the potential.

00:59:32.749 --> 00:59:34.290
And so for simplicity,
I'm also going

00:59:34.290 --> 00:59:36.123
to start with energy
greater than the height

00:59:36.123 --> 00:59:40.511
of the potential, v0, and
then we'll do e less than v0

00:59:40.511 --> 00:59:41.010
afterwards.

00:59:41.010 --> 00:59:42.926
It'll be an easy extension
of what we've done.

00:59:46.760 --> 00:59:50.217
OK, so this will be our
first case to study.

00:59:50.217 --> 00:59:52.300
So we know the form of the
wave function out here,

00:59:52.300 --> 00:59:54.815
it's a e to the ikx,
b to the minus ikx.

00:59:54.815 --> 00:59:56.440
We know that for the
potential out here

00:59:56.440 --> 00:59:58.499
it's c e to the ikx and
d e to the minus ikx.

00:59:58.499 --> 01:00:00.165
The only thing we
don't know is the form

01:00:00.165 --> 01:00:02.117
of the potential in here.

01:00:02.117 --> 01:00:03.700
And in here it's
actually very simple.

01:00:03.700 --> 01:00:05.430
It's got to be something
of the form-- I

01:00:05.430 --> 01:00:07.920
think I called it
f and g, I did.

