This was a finitely
high barrier.

01:12:34.590 --> 01:12:37.191
Large energies, we
don't even notice it.

01:12:37.191 --> 01:12:39.210
It tells you at low
energies-- well,

01:12:39.210 --> 01:12:41.570
we don't know yet what
happens at very low energies.

01:12:41.570 --> 01:12:44.805
But at reasonably low energies,
the transmission is suppressed.

01:12:44.805 --> 01:12:46.430
And if you sort of
squint, this roughly

01:12:46.430 --> 01:12:48.530
does what we'd expect
from the step barrier.

01:12:48.530 --> 01:12:50.460
However, something
really special

01:12:50.460 --> 01:12:52.472
is happening at special
values of epsilon.

01:12:52.472 --> 01:12:53.930
We're getting
perfect transmission.

01:12:56.710 --> 01:13:01.390
We get perfect transmission of
these points, t is equal to 1.

01:13:01.390 --> 01:13:02.550
Perfect.

01:13:02.550 --> 01:13:03.050
Star.

01:13:05.890 --> 01:13:06.860
Happy with a big nose.

01:13:06.860 --> 01:13:07.840
I don't know.

01:13:07.840 --> 01:13:10.560
Perfect transmission
at all these points.

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:16.042
So this leaves us with
a question of why.

01:13:16.042 --> 01:13:17.620
Why the perfect
transmission, what's

01:13:17.620 --> 01:13:20.320
the mechanism making
transmission perfect.

01:13:20.320 --> 01:13:22.630
But it also does something
really lovely for us.

01:13:22.630 --> 01:13:26.280
Suppose you see a spectrum, you
see a transmission amplitude

01:13:26.280 --> 01:13:28.630
or transmission probability
that looks like this.

01:13:28.630 --> 01:13:29.900
You may get crappy data.

01:13:29.900 --> 01:13:31.289
You may see that
it's smudged out

01:13:31.289 --> 01:13:32.830
and you see all
sorts of messy stuff.

01:13:32.830 --> 01:13:35.210
But if you know that
there's perfect transmission

01:13:35.210 --> 01:13:37.430
at some particular
epsilon 1, there's

01:13:37.430 --> 01:13:40.180
more perfect transmission at
another epsilon 2, more perfect

01:13:40.180 --> 01:13:41.900
transmission at
epsilon 3, and they

01:13:41.900 --> 01:13:43.750
scale, they fit to
this prediction.

01:13:43.750 --> 01:13:45.487
What do you know?

01:13:45.487 --> 01:13:47.070
That you've got a
finite high barrier,

01:13:47.070 --> 01:13:52.047
and it's probably pretty well
approximated by a square step.

01:13:52.047 --> 01:13:54.630
So in your problem set, you're
going to get experimental data,

01:13:54.630 --> 01:13:57.882
and you're going to have to
match to the experimental data.

01:13:57.882 --> 01:13:59.590
You're going to have
to predict something

01:13:59.590 --> 01:14:02.320
about the potential that created
a particular transmission

01:14:02.320 --> 01:14:03.730
probability distribution.

01:14:03.730 --> 01:14:05.449
And knowing where
these resonances are,

01:14:05.449 --> 01:14:07.240
where these points of
perfect transmission,

01:14:07.240 --> 01:14:08.490
is going to be very
useful for you.

01:14:08.490 --> 01:14:08.989
Yeah.

01:14:08.989 --> 01:14:10.866
AUDIENCE: Wasn't there
another potential

01:14:10.866 --> 01:14:13.920
that will also
create periodic 1s?

01:14:13.920 --> 01:14:15.370
PROFESSOR: A very good question.

01:14:15.370 --> 01:14:17.520
So I'm going to turn
that around to you.

01:14:17.520 --> 01:14:20.790
Can you orchestrate a potential
that gives you the same thing?

01:14:24.092 --> 01:14:25.800
That's an interesting
empirical question.

01:14:25.800 --> 01:14:30.350
So, on the problem set, you'll
study a double well potential.

01:14:30.350 --> 01:14:32.121
So the question
was, how do I know

01:14:32.121 --> 01:14:34.370
isn't another potential that
gives me the same answer?

01:14:34.370 --> 01:14:35.200
At this point, we don't know.

01:14:35.200 --> 01:14:36.300
Maybe there is
another potential.

01:14:36.300 --> 01:14:37.850
In fact, you can do
all sorts of things

01:14:37.850 --> 01:14:40.100
to make a potential that's
very arbitrarily close that

01:14:40.100 --> 01:14:43.000
gives you an arbitrarily
similar profile.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:45.296
So if they're
significantly different,

01:14:45.296 --> 01:14:46.615
how different do they look?

01:14:46.615 --> 01:14:48.490
So then the students
say, well, I don't know.

01:14:48.490 --> 01:14:49.650
What about a double
well potential?

01:14:49.650 --> 01:14:51.774
So, in fact, we'll be doing
a double well potential

01:14:51.774 --> 01:14:54.600
on the problem set.

01:14:54.600 --> 01:14:55.370
A good question.

01:14:55.370 --> 01:14:56.640
And we certainly
haven't proven anything

01:14:56.640 --> 01:14:57.900
like this is the
only potentially

01:14:57.900 --> 01:14:59.420
that gives you this
transmission amplitude.

01:14:59.420 --> 01:15:01.794
What we can say is if you get
transmission amplitude that

01:15:01.794 --> 01:15:04.550
looks like this, it's
probably pretty reasonable

01:15:04.550 --> 01:15:07.796
to say it's probably
well modeled.

01:15:07.796 --> 01:15:09.920
We seem to be reproducing
the data reasonably well.

01:15:09.920 --> 01:15:12.600
So it's not a proof of
anything, but it's a nice model.

01:15:12.600 --> 01:15:15.200
And we're physicists,
we build models.

01:15:15.200 --> 01:15:17.990
We don't tell you
what's true, we

01:15:17.990 --> 01:15:20.594
tell you what are good models.

01:15:20.594 --> 01:15:22.010
If a theorist ever
walks up on you

01:15:22.010 --> 01:15:27.410
and he says, here's the
truth, punch him in the gut.

01:15:27.410 --> 01:15:28.960
That's not how it works.

01:15:28.960 --> 01:15:30.852
Experimentalists,
on the other hand.

01:15:30.852 --> 01:15:32.310
We'll just punch
them too, I guess.

01:15:32.310 --> 01:15:36.264
[LAUGHTER]

01:15:36.264 --> 01:15:38.330
PROFESSOR: We build models.

01:15:38.330 --> 01:15:42.580
OK, so this leaves us
with an obvious question,

01:15:42.580 --> 01:15:47.210
which we've answer
in the case of energy

01:15:47.210 --> 01:15:50.030
grade in the potential.

01:15:50.030 --> 01:15:53.571
What about the case of the
energy less than the potential.

01:15:53.571 --> 01:15:55.570
So we haven't filled out
that part of the graph.

01:15:55.570 --> 01:15:57.153
Let's fill out that
part of the graph.

01:15:57.153 --> 01:16:00.020
What happens if the energy
is less than the potential?

01:16:00.020 --> 01:16:03.190
And for this, I'm going to
use the trick that I mentioned

01:16:03.190 --> 01:16:04.696
earlier that, look,
if the energy is

01:16:04.696 --> 01:16:06.570
less than the potential,
that just means that

01:16:06.570 --> 01:16:09.574
in the intervening
regime, in here,

01:16:09.574 --> 01:16:10.990
instead of being
oscillatory, it's

01:16:10.990 --> 01:16:13.550
going to be exponentially
growing [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:13.550 --> 01:16:15.940
because we're in a
classically disallowed region.

01:16:15.940 --> 01:16:17.410
So if the energy
is less than v0,

01:16:17.410 --> 01:16:21.200
here we have instead of
ikx, we have minus alpha x.

01:16:21.200 --> 01:16:25.750
And instead of minus ikx
we have plus alpha x.

01:16:25.750 --> 01:16:28.010
So if you go through
that whole analysis

01:16:28.010 --> 01:16:32.400
and plug in those values for
the k prime, the answer you get

01:16:32.400 --> 01:16:33.570
is really quite nice.

01:16:33.570 --> 01:16:38.174
We find that t for energy
less than v0 is equal to--

01:16:38.174 --> 01:16:40.340
and it's just a direct
analytic continuation of what

01:16:40.340 --> 01:16:51.571
you get here-- 1 plus 1 over
4 epsilon 1 minus epsilon.

01:16:51.571 --> 01:16:52.820
So epsilon is less than 1 now.

01:16:56.516 --> 01:17:08.050
1 sinh squared of g0 1
minus epsilon under 1.

01:17:08.050 --> 01:17:09.965
OK, so now this lets
us complete the plot.

01:17:13.812 --> 01:17:15.770
And you can check, it's
pretty straightforward,

01:17:15.770 --> 01:17:18.230
that because sinh, again,
goes like its argument

01:17:18.230 --> 01:17:20.020
at very small values
of its argument,

01:17:20.020 --> 01:17:23.000
we get g0 squared
1 minus epsilon.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:27.130
Sorry, this should be
square root 1 minus epsilon.

01:17:27.130 --> 01:17:27.680
Really?

01:17:27.680 --> 01:17:28.896
Is that a typo?

01:17:28.896 --> 01:17:29.770
Oh no, it's in there.

01:17:29.770 --> 01:17:32.510
OK, good.

01:17:32.510 --> 01:17:34.580
So again, we get g0
squared 1 minus epsilon,

01:17:34.580 --> 01:17:38.282
the 1 minus epsilon cancels,
and we get 1 over 4 g0 squared.

01:17:38.282 --> 01:17:39.990
Which is good, because
if they disagreed,

01:17:39.990 --> 01:17:42.050
we'd be in real trouble.

01:17:42.050 --> 01:17:44.740
So they agree, but the sinh
squared is just a strictly--

01:17:44.740 --> 01:17:46.920
or that function is just
a strictly decreasing

01:17:46.920 --> 01:17:48.670
function as we approach
epsilon goes to 0.

01:17:48.670 --> 01:17:50.320
It goes mostly to 0.

01:17:50.320 --> 01:17:51.300
So this is what we see.

01:17:51.300 --> 01:17:53.890
We see an exponential
region and then

01:17:53.890 --> 01:17:57.820
we see oscillations
with residences

01:17:57.820 --> 01:18:01.780
where the period is
getting wider and wider.

01:18:01.780 --> 01:18:04.379
But this should trouble
you a little bit.

01:18:04.379 --> 01:18:05.420
Here, what are we saying?

01:18:05.420 --> 01:18:09.570
We're saying look,
if we have a barrier,

01:18:09.570 --> 01:18:12.010
and we send in a
particle with energy way

01:18:12.010 --> 01:18:18.012
below the barrier,
that's kind of troubling.

01:18:18.012 --> 01:18:20.470
If we send in a particle with
energy way below the barrier,

01:18:20.470 --> 01:18:22.860
there's some probability
that it gets out.

01:18:22.860 --> 01:18:23.610
It goes across.

01:18:27.980 --> 01:18:35.340
So for e less than v0,
classically no transmission,

01:18:35.340 --> 01:18:36.800
we get transmission.

01:18:36.800 --> 01:18:44.447
Now, do we get resonances
when e is less than v0?

01:18:44.447 --> 01:18:45.780
No, that's an interesting thing.

01:18:45.780 --> 01:18:47.900
We'll talk about resonances
and where they come from,

01:18:47.900 --> 01:18:50.360
and we'll talk about the more
generalized notion of a nest

01:18:50.360 --> 01:18:52.150
matrix in the next lecture.

01:18:52.150 --> 01:18:55.860
But for now I just want to say
a couple of things about it.

01:18:55.860 --> 01:19:00.700
So I want to ask-- so
this is called tunneling,

01:19:00.700 --> 01:19:06.240
this transmission across
a disallowed barrier,

01:19:06.240 --> 01:19:14.841
a classically
disallowed barrier--

01:19:14.841 --> 01:19:16.840
so this transmission
across a disallowed barrier

01:19:16.840 --> 01:19:19.910
is called tunneling.

01:19:19.910 --> 01:19:26.000
And just a quick thing to notice
is that if we hold e fixed

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:29.496
and we vary l, we vary
the width of the barrier,

01:19:29.496 --> 01:19:31.120
how does the tunneling
amplitude depend

01:19:31.120 --> 01:19:33.120
on the width of the barrier?

01:19:33.120 --> 01:19:37.140
At fixed energy, if we vary the
width of the barrier-- which

01:19:37.140 --> 01:19:40.527
is only contained
in g0-- how does

01:19:40.527 --> 01:19:41.860
the transmission amplitude vary?

01:19:41.860 --> 01:19:45.450
And we find that for large
l-- for l much greater than 1

01:19:45.450 --> 01:19:46.950
for a typical scale
in the problem--

01:19:46.950 --> 01:19:54.180
the tunneling amplitude goes
like e to the minus 2 alpha l

01:19:54.180 --> 01:19:58.049
where alpha just depends on
the energy in the potential.

01:19:58.049 --> 01:20:00.340
So what we see is that the
probability of transmitting,

01:20:00.340 --> 01:20:03.170
of tunneling through
a wall, depends

01:20:03.170 --> 01:20:04.610
on the width of that wall.

01:20:04.610 --> 01:20:06.830
And it depends on
it exponentially.

01:20:06.830 --> 01:20:09.300
The wider the wall, the
exponentially less likely you

01:20:09.300 --> 01:20:10.420
are to tunnel across it.

01:20:10.420 --> 01:20:12.280
And this fits the
simulation we ran

01:20:12.280 --> 01:20:15.530
where we saw that tunnelling
through a very thin wall

01:20:15.530 --> 01:20:17.590
was actually quite efficient.

01:20:17.590 --> 01:20:20.260
And we also saw that
tunnelling across a wall

01:20:20.260 --> 01:20:21.260
can have resonant peaks.

01:20:21.260 --> 01:20:23.584
At special values, it
transmits perfectly.

01:20:23.584 --> 01:20:24.875
We saw that in the simulations.

01:20:29.396 --> 01:20:32.020
So at this point I can't resist
telling you a very short story.

01:20:32.020 --> 01:20:35.620
I have a very good friend
who is not a physicist,

01:20:35.620 --> 01:20:37.880
but who is a professor at MIT.

01:20:37.880 --> 01:20:41.810
So a smart person,
and very smart.

01:20:41.810 --> 01:20:43.890
She's one of the
smartest people I know.

01:20:43.890 --> 01:20:47.170
She broke her ankle.

01:20:47.170 --> 01:20:49.880
She's always losing stuff,
she's constantly losing stuff.

01:20:49.880 --> 01:20:54.840
And she broke her ankle, and she
was going to the rehab place,

01:20:54.840 --> 01:20:58.635
and she parked her car right
in front of the rehab place.

01:20:58.635 --> 01:21:00.010
She parked her
car right in front

01:21:00.010 --> 01:21:01.250
because she's got
the broken ankle

01:21:01.250 --> 01:21:03.130
and she doesn't want to have to
walk a long way to get the car,

01:21:03.130 --> 01:21:04.370
she parked right in front.

01:21:04.370 --> 01:21:06.660
She went in, she did
her two hours of rehab,

01:21:06.660 --> 01:21:10.740
and she came outside,
and her car was gone.

01:21:10.740 --> 01:21:12.575
And she's always
misplacing her car,

01:21:12.575 --> 01:21:13.950
she's always
misplacing her keys,

01:21:13.950 --> 01:21:15.241
she's always losing everything.

01:21:15.241 --> 01:21:19.750
But this time, this time
she knew where it was.

01:21:19.750 --> 01:21:21.380
And it wasn't there.

01:21:21.380 --> 01:21:24.777
So first she thought, oh
crap, my car's been stolen.

01:21:24.777 --> 01:21:26.360
How annoying, I've
got a broken ankle.

01:21:26.360 --> 01:21:28.262
But she looks
around, and there's

01:21:28.262 --> 01:21:30.220
her car on the other side
of the street pointed

01:21:30.220 --> 01:21:32.700
the opposite direction.

01:21:32.700 --> 01:21:36.340
And she's like, finally.

01:21:36.340 --> 01:21:36.910
Finally.

01:21:36.910 --> 01:21:39.235
She was explaining this to
me and a friend of mine who

01:21:39.235 --> 01:21:41.760
is also a physicist,
she said finally, I

01:21:41.760 --> 01:21:45.710
knew I had incontrovertible
proof that quantum

01:21:45.710 --> 01:21:47.990
effects happen to
macroscopic objects.

01:21:47.990 --> 01:21:50.300
My car tunnelled
across the street.

01:21:50.300 --> 01:21:51.890
[LAUGHTER]

01:21:51.890 --> 01:21:53.390
PROFESSOR: At this
point, of course,

01:21:53.390 --> 01:21:55.490
my friend and I are
just dying of laughter.

01:21:55.490 --> 01:21:57.560
But she said my car
tunnelled across the street.

01:21:57.560 --> 01:22:00.290
But here's the problem,
I couldn't tell anyone.

01:22:00.290 --> 01:22:03.340
Because if I told anyone, they
would know that I was crazy.

01:22:03.340 --> 01:22:07.000
Clearly I'm crazy, because I
lose my stuff all the time,

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:08.870
but surely it's just
gotten misplaced.

01:22:08.870 --> 01:22:10.820
So I went home, and
I got home and I

01:22:10.820 --> 01:22:13.400
was sitting down to dinner with
my partner and our daughter

01:22:13.400 --> 01:22:16.120
and I was burning up
inside because I wanted

01:22:16.120 --> 01:22:18.020
to tell them this
crazy thing happened.

01:22:18.020 --> 01:22:20.817
I know quantum
mechanics, it happens.

01:22:20.817 --> 01:22:22.650
I couldn't tell them
anything, so I was just

01:22:22.650 --> 01:22:23.530
fidgeting and dying.

01:22:23.530 --> 01:22:26.380
And finally my
daughter said, mom,

01:22:26.380 --> 01:22:29.190
didn't you notice that we moved
the car across the street?

01:22:29.190 --> 01:22:31.520
[LAUGHTER]

01:22:31.520 --> 01:22:33.660
PROFESSOR: See you next time.

